<br>
<br>
Anyone who's been around playing MUD's and various MMORPG's knows that concepts like perma-death and unique, one-time events are not new ideas. <br>
<br>
Creating the Sleeper script was a way for Verant to test out an idea. A one-time, unique, unreversible event. <br>
<br>
And they have got to see first-hand how it has impacted the game, the players, and the community of a server as a whole. <br>
<br>
<br>
Designers can debate the merits of a design concept until they are blue in the face, but until you put that idea into a live realm and let real players react to it, you never can tell for certain how it will play out. <br>
<br>
<br>
I think the Sleeper was a beta-test for possible future similiar events. And after the way it's turned out, I'd be surprised if we see any more one-shot events like this. <br>
<br>
<br>
In the end, we all play to be the hero. Events like Waking the Sleeper prevent a large portion of the player-base from experiencing that event. That's disappointing. <br>
<br>
I believe that what is &quot;fair&quot; is the &quot;opportunity&quot;. If everyone has the same &quot;opportunity&quot; to do something, that's fair. Everyone may not be able to do it, because maybe they don't have high enough level, or a big enough guild, but the &quot;opportunity&quot; is still there. Just like an epic weapon - the chance to complete always exists, you just have to muster up the forces and timing to do it. <br>
<br>
But waking the Sleeper, once done, doesn't afford everyone else the same &quot;opportunity&quot;. It's done, and that's it... <br>
<br>
Maybe on a small server, with few people, and a constantly changing and evolving world, this type of event would be worthwhile. But in EQ things don't change permanently. You can kill Naggy at least once a week.. <br>
<br>
It seems out-of-place to me to put a permanent event like Waking the Sleeper in a perpetual-running world...<br>
<br>
-Krazak<br>
